One thing you notice in early physiology texts is when they talk about "action of the muscles", muscular movement following off an acquired reflex, etc. the reader is supposed to imagine e.g. a man playing the violin, but a modern reader tends to associate such language w/ sports

Like any time muscular movements are mentioned for me the first association is running, jumping, pushing weights, etc. while it is actually meant to convey more precise skillful actions like the work of a sculptor. Shows how more barbaric we (I) have become today in comparison.

One time I asked my buddy what he would do if he had dictatorial powers over our city and his response was like "install water fountains on every street corner and make it mandatory for residential buildings to be covered from top to bottom in grapevines for the making of wine".

Genuinely sublime vision of Soviet era panel apartment blocks literally drowning in grapes, men in autumn hauling heavy wine-presses onto the concrete and producing gallons upon gallons of wine, fermenting smell thick in the air, birds playing in the pristine fountains, children.

Curious how everyone has such a different reaction to encountering a snake outdoors. Like one of my friends (gourmand, old school type guy) just steps over it, zero care. Another (very brave otherwise, most high test man I know) sees one in the distance and immediately runs back.

It's a very primordial thing, mammal even, so a person's deeper self is sometimes incidentally revealed beyond social norms, intentional behavior etc. Me, I jump once I spot one, then immediately calm and return to rationality, but afterwards keep hallucinating them in the grass.
